Évaluation publiée le 16 janvier 2021
A quick little linear adventure game telling a grim story of the world, and their desperate want for water. The main character, after everyone has met their end, begins his adventure to the 4th tower, the tallest of the 4 towers featured in this game. You go along reading diaries and fixing the towers. The ending touched me in a way that I feel would be too revealing of the rest of the game to include, however i found it to be suiting for the character and his outlook. Overall for a game that took 12 seconds to install, and being free, I would give this game a chance, truly a great experience.

Évaluation publiée le 15 janvier 2021
Достучаться до небес
Cloud Climber – микроскопический 15-минутный симулятор ходьбы от инди-студии Two Star Games, выпустившей, к примеру, хоррор My Beautiful Paper Smile, в котором, как и в предыдущих их проектах, используется в своём роде приятный «рисованный от руки» визуальный стиль окружения. Однако помимо этого, в игре есть неожиданно занятное содержательное наполнение. О нём в основном и поговорим.

Главный герой – строитель одной из множества башен, возвышающихся над землёй и постоянно растущих к облакам, которые в свою очередь поднимаются всё выше. В один день ему вздумалось пойти на одну из соседних башен (всего мы их посетим четыре) и закончить работу. О предыстории этой стройки века распространяться не буду, однако мы будем находить дневники, из которых, помимо лора, узнаем в том числе и небольшие отрывки из жизни рабочих – забавные, грустные и просто эмоциональные душеизлияния. Правда, основные сюжетные линии и моменты всё равно останутся нераскрытыми и незавершёнными, да и исследовать даже доступные башни нам не дадут (по три-четыре этажа на каждой максимум), но образность концовки, тем не менее, оставляет приятное впечатление и намекает на общую метафоричность происходящего.

Если вам нужно чем-либо занять свободные 15 минут, эта игра вполне может подойти. Конечно никакого значительного игрового опыта от неё получить не получится (два-три элементарных взаимодействия с предметами не считаются), но потенциал у подобного проекта явно присутствует, были бы местный лор, интерактивность и размеры игрового мира более развиты. Но как всегда, игра бесплатная, а значит, учитывая горы шлака по несоизмеримо высоким ценам, всё равно неплохо.

6 из 10 – удовлетворительно
Спасибо, что прочли этот обзор! Если не трудно, оцените, насколько он был вам полезен, и можете посмотреть другие обзоры в моём профиле ;)
 
Condor Freedman

Évaluation publiée le 31 janvier 2021
《攀云者》：渴雨世界的筑塔之人

简短但却气氛十足的免费步行模拟游戏，讲述了某个处于中世纪水平的世界在多年前完全停止了降雨，江河湖海逐渐干涸，危害性的尘暴笼罩了地面，生命正迈向枯竭和灭亡。数百年来，人们挣扎求生，拼尽一切资源自地表修建起无数座通天高塔，渴望触及云端获得珍贵的水源，但无数代筑塔人的努力最终都化作了泡影。

在资源愈发紧缺的绝望气氛中，一些塔楼上的人们甚至开始互相内斗，为自保争夺仅存的补给与水资源，只求能苟延残喘久一些。而这些无谓争斗的结局自然是悲剧性的。

男主是他家族最后的幸存者，已经孤身一人的他自知已了无希望，于是在这一天决定踏上最后的高塔巡礼之旅。脚下是被无边尘霾覆盖的绝望大地，登上附近高塔之巅的男主却在环视四周那些象征人们不屈求生信念的高塔后，由衷地发出了「真美丽啊」的感慨。

在塔顶坐下的男主准备平静地迎接自己的终结，然而他的耳畔却响起了生平从未听过的声音：那是隆隆作响的雷声。很快，天空中就有雨水淅淅沥沥地落下，男主见证了奇迹。

这个世界在很久以前完全停止了降雨，天空不再将水——这珍贵的生命之源赐予大地，窒息的尘暴席卷一切夺走了原本蔚蓝的天空，世界不可避免地迈向枯竭与死亡。不甘接受命运的人们开始竭力寻求自我救赎，数百年来一代代筑塔人倾尽一生让座座通天高塔拔地而起，人们渴望着，有朝一日能够触摸云端获得水源。 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : 呆罗

男主是筑塔一族最后的幸存者，辗转登上未完成的最后一座塔楼的顶端，感概脚下多年来无数筑塔人倾尽一生创造的塔楼奇观的美丽，自知再无希望的他决定放下担子平静地接受最后的命运。然而，生平从未听过的声音开始出现于他的耳畔，隆隆雷声后雨滴淅淅沥沥地从天而降。奇迹出现，世界终于得到了救赎。 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : 呆罗


干涸的世界终于迎来了久违的甘霖——世界，复苏了。


游戏大约 10-15 分钟就能通关，没有解密要素。虽是末世背景，但游戏整体氛围却显得非常平静，一路伴随男主沉静的独白向上攀登欣赏四周高塔林立的奇景，途中可以收集到一系列笔记了解世界观和故事。结尾处的处理则是点睛之笔，在枯木逢春式的感触中拉高了作品整体的立意。总得来说是相当推荐大家抽一点时间去体验的精品免费步行模拟游戏。

Évaluation publiée le 17 janvier 2021
A short impression/review/feedback (Call it what you will!) of a short game (Takes about 10-20 minutes to finish).

It is a free title.. I am usually wary of such titles as I have a deep belief that somehow quality and cost are directly proportional to each others. This game struck me as good as many other titles I actually paid for, decent and worth playing!

It is about humanity's desperate measures to survive.. About their short sightedness and late reactions.. About their greed, selfishness and even their love.. About miracles! Many angles to look at the game from, all within 10-20 minutes of just walking around.

I am mainly reviewing to raise attention to this game that would probably go unnoticed for many. If you are into walking sims, you probably would like this game.. Even if you don't, it is free and very short.. No harm's done in trying!

Évaluation publiée le 29 janvier 2021
Ever thought mankind, in order to save itself, will start building towers? Towers to reach the skies but more importantly to reach the clouds to get access to water. Water that somehow disappeared or got contaminated hundreds of years ago. Rationing of this substance is important just as continuing the construction while dust storms become more prevailing.

An interesting premise, all stored within a 15-minute long walking sim. This is what Cloud Climber is. No real challenges just walking upwards while finding notes to get more background info on this dystopian - and at the same time surreal - future. It's short but free and it is completely free of charge.

Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : Nuit Calme

Cloud Climber is not a game; it's a tiny, beautiful, and polished experience that would honestly look so much better if presented as a short story or a short film rather than a Steam product. How do I put it... If Cloud Climber was a person that could feel and think, I'm sure they would be uncomfortable in this unwieldy, cumbersome body of a videogame and would much rather exist as words on a page to truly realise their potential.

I thoroughly enjoyed the little notes scattered around the towers; in the 20 minutes that it took me to finish Cloud Climber, I went from having absolutely no idea what was going on, to silently wishing there was no answer to this mystery lest it leaves me in bitter disappointment, to eventually being impressed with how the developer managed to conclude the story without botching the job and making everything either too grandiose and pompous or too shallow and inexpressive. I know for a fact that it is very challenging to find that golden middle, and this is the main reason why I believe Cloud Climber is more of a creative writing achievement rather than a compelling videogame. I kid you not, there is even a subplot – masterfully woven into the main story, somewhat tragic but with a slight comic relief – all of the ingredients that make the dish called "I'm a great writer, but I don't take myself too seriously". Bravo!

I might be wrong, but it looks like the creator voiced the main character, too. Truly a person of many talents – an aspiring videogame developer, a promising writer and an impressive voice actor. One skill that I would gently suggest should be paid more attention to is proofreading... In a game that sits you down to tell you a story, the last thing you want to see are jarring grammar mistakes!
 
Nuit Calme

Évaluation publiée le 16 janvier 2021
Cloud Climber es una experiencia de lo más entretenida. El juego es muy corto, se puede pasar en 10 o 15 minutos dependiendo de la exploración.

La aventura empieza desde una perspectiva en la que se observan una serie de torres sin terminar. Nuestro protagonista va narrando los sucesos de lo que pasó.

Desde hace muchas décadas, en la Tierra dejó de llover haciendo que el planeta se secara. Debido a la sequedad, cada mes hacían aparición tormentas de arena. Los habitantes construyeron torres para intentar llegar a las nubes y conseguir el agua que tanto necesitaban. Tras 100 años intentando conseguir ese agua, las esperanzas se desvanecieron haciendo que las torres quedaran sin terminar.
Ahora nuestro personaje debe ir a la última torre más alta y seguir construyendo lo que quedó para acabar lo que no se pudo conseguir.

Pese a que haya sido corto, el juego te hace ver una reflexión de todos los esfuerzos de aquella gente que no se rendía ante la posibilidad de conseguir reservas de agua.

Os recomiendo mucho jugarlo. Aunque sea una experiencia corta te hace pensar en lo que se ve hoy en día en el mundo.

Évaluation publiée le 16 avril 2021
Produit reçu gratuitement

It's my husband's first time playing a story-driven walking sim. game on Steam.

The Experience:

Although my husband still needs practice on getting used to using the AWSD/arrow keys + a mouse to play games, we both liked the concept of the story and the scenery.

Items and interact-able items are easy to spot. Items are automatically used when you interact with a prompt object. So players do not need to worry about having an inventory bag.

I love the notes left behind by the previous tower workers showing the situation of shortage of water, and how the main character's older generations began building these towers. And when all hopes seem to have gone, rain comes!!

Who would like this game:

I would recommend this game to new users of Steam, people who like a short story. The game story is set in a post-war world where nature has been seriously polluted.

Nothing scary or death or to hide. Just a calm quiet player isolated alone on the top of the wooden towers built by his grandfather + realistic wind sound BG effects. Atmospheric environment.

Summary:

Simple game, yet the creator is able to bring out the story's message that he wish to deliver, without frustrating the player(all guided and prompted hints).

Évaluation publiée le 17 janvier 2021
Browsing through Steam, I was surprised to find something like this. Cloud Climber is a walking simulator, where you are the last worker in a group of towers designed to collect water from the clouds above. Unfortunately, the towers were never completed, so capturing water from the clouds never happened. Even more unfortunate, you are potentially the last surviving human in at the end of the world where there is no water on the ground. As you progress, you hear what the protagonist thinks as he traverses each tower, read notes from the presumably deceased workers, and solve basic puzzles to continue.

The game's setting is pretty, but the story leaves much to be desired. In my playthrough, I completed the game in only 15 minutes, which leaves little room for the player to become immersed in the story. Another immersion breaker I found to be the notes that were suppose to supplement the story. This wasn't because the notes were poorly written, rather that they were comically close to each other where you would read how one worker despised another, and then right next to it was a note from the worker the previous one complained about. If some of the notes were spaced farther apart, this would have been a little less of an issue.

Despite my criticisms, I am in no position to give this game a thumbs down. Cloud Climber manages to tell a coherent story with many of the details hidden from the player, which may be a downside, but also adds to the story's intrigue. Also, Cloud Climber is free! For a first person experience to be this polished and free, I cannot be too critical.

Give Cloud Climber a play if you ever have some time to spare. Oh, and don't get too close to the ledge.



Unrelated question: How did none of the workers succumb to Hypoxia at such a high altitude??

Évaluation publiée le 25 janvier 2021
I'll get it out of the way: yeah, Cloud Climber is short... but who gives a crap? Since when has length, price, complexity, or aesthetic ever mattered in assigning value to a piece of art? I would argue that the brevity, price-tag (or lack thereof), simplicity, and straightforwardness of this game makes it - and its ending - as accessible as humanly possible.

Cloud Climber does not attempt to impress the player with anything other than its creation of atmosphere (both literally and figuratively) and its developer's storytelling capability. Needless to say, but I was very impressed. I think the creator sends 2 messages for Cloud Climber to deliver and for the player to receive (as far as I can tell, at least), and I think that it would be really hard to argue against either of them. I don't mean to end this part of my review on a cliffhanger, but just play it; play Cloud Climber, a 20 minute process from starting the download to experiencing the ending, and I'm sure you'll come up with the 2 messages that I'm including in the spoiler section.

I think the two messages were to (A) save the planet and (B) to admire your own work/value the journey, not just the destination. There's quite a few details to read into like: the note(s) from Kyle mentioned that he would fight for his own greed (even though he knew that the end was coming for him too) or how Karl thought it was hilarious to pretend to push someone off the edge of the tower... until that person flinched while close enough to the edge that they really did fall off the edge of the tower. Cloud Climber really has a lot to say about us humans and, if we don't start working together sometime in the very near future, one of us could be the protagonist sitting atop the tower, contemplating their journey of themselves, their neighbors, and their ancestors desperately trying at the very last minute to stop themselves from succumbing to the very same disaster we knew we were creating for ourselves (climate change). Seriously, people, we gotta cut out the carbon (and the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥), and start saving this planet before we die along with it.

If anyone actually read this whole thing: thank you very, very much! I hope you have a great day, and I hope that I formatted the spoiler section correctly. Also, I wish I could have remembered all of the ideas that came to me while typing something else... there was a lot of good stuff that I just plain forgot to write down.

Wer hat den höchsten?
Ab und an entdeckt man in den Massen kostenloser Spiele auf Steam ein wunderbares Kleinod. Cloud Climber von Two Star Games ist so eines: Kurz, stringent und absolut empfehlenswert.

Die vergangene Zukunft – Geschichte und Art des Spiels
Wir sind Bewohner einer Einheit aus Türmen, die ihr Leben lang versuchen, durch Erhöhung ihres Turms die Wolken zu erreichen. Denn es fehlt an Nahrung und vor allem Wasser. Kein Wunder, dass Neid, Missgunst und Größenwahn da nicht auf sich warten lassen. Aber wir sind der letzte Überlebende und haben es selbst in der Hand.

Tower ambience 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : Godofhellfire

Cloud Climber ist ein einfacher Walking Simulator mit wenigen Rätseln und kleinen Geschichten, die in Tagebucheinträgen präsentiert werden. Das ergibt ein schönes stringentes Erlebnis.

Papier trägt nicht – Technisches und Sonstiges
Die Grafik hat mir sehr gefallen, ein guter Weitblick, gepaart mit bleistiftgezeichneter Umgebung und 3D-Objekten – da hat jemand sein Handwerk gemeistert. Die musikalische Untermalung ist unauffällig passend, die Technik funktioniert ohne Fehler.
Bevor man sich aber den ganzen Abend freihält: Die Reise dauert 15 Minuten, ist aber dankenswerterweise kostenlos.

Eine 15-minütige Reise am Puls der Zeit, ein Turmsteig-Simulator mit kleinen und einer großen Geschichte. Wohin nur, wenn nicht zu den Wolken?

Lust auf mehr Reviews mit einmal mehr und einmal weniger archäologischen Anmerkungen? Probier doch meine Kuratoren-Gruppe The Archaeologist plays… aus.

Évaluation publiée le 18 novembre 2022
This isn't really a game. Heck, it's barely even a demo... there are longer-lasting demos. I played for a full 36 minutes and about half of that was spent alt-tabbed out to Windows. Veeeeeery very short walking sim.

PROS:
- That being said, in terms of game mechanics it has no real flaws, although as-is there isn't enough there to cause flaws.
- And the graphics style is pretty nice. I like the sort of Bendy style of the look.
- I also enjoyed the story-building, such as it was. It's impressive that in such a short experience the dev is able to thread together the start of a pretty solid-feeling story.

♥♥♥♥:
- Again... not much here. I mean you could seriously finish this in 5 minutes if you ignored the story notes, and probably less than that if you know exactly where the super small handful of items you need to pick up are at. Free though, ehh. Not the biggest ♥♥♥ ever.
- The narration bothered me. Someone in the protagonist's position wouldn't sound like this, like he's just sort of halfheartedly musing over his ultimate demise that he sees coming after realizing that he's the only one left - I would expect this level of concern over whether he'll have the hamburger or the hotdog for lunch today, not over your life ending. If this were to turn into something bigger, they'd probably want to do something about that. I realize this may just be a solo project though.
- But to dovetail off that last thought, this was clearly meant to end with the ending provided, so it wasn't a demo for things to come, no cliffhangers or 'to be continued' expectations here. Which I do see as a flaw, since this feels like it could be something a lot cooler if more effort were put towards it.
- Lastly, while not sure if this is my fault or the game's fault, somehow this title managed to drag my 3080ti, framelocked at 120fps, all the way up to almost 75c. It certainly added to the ambiance of being up on a tower in the sky, because my computer sounded like the wind. As there is no way to change anything in the settings related to graphics - any changes must be done from your graphics card GUI app, other than just setting general quality, which doesn't actually change anything in-game - I'm moreso blaming the programming for this one.

So while I won't say this is a good "game," I will say that this is a great practice run or tech demo, hopefully with takeaway improvements for future titles from this dev.

UPDATE: Ahh, well this explains quite a bit: "Cloud Climber is a short story based game that I made in one week for the 2020 Epic MegaJam, which took place in December."

Ok one week is pretty nuts!

In einem letzten Akt der Verzweiflung bauen die Menschen Türme, die hoch in den Himmel reichen. Warum werden sie gebaut? Und werden sie ihren Zweck erfüllen?

Évaluation publiée le 15 septembre 2023
Ein sehr kurze Laufsimulation mit toller Atmosphäre.

Über den Wolken 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : Keks

Geschichte

Um an Wasser zu kommen, das in den Wolken "festhängt" wurde vor Jahrhunderten begonnen, Holztürme zu bauen (die scheinbar immer höher werden mussten). Wir sind jetzt wohl (in dieser Gegend) der Letzte seiner Art und machen uns auf den Weg, hin zu anderen Türmen.

Die Geschichte ist eher in einer magischen Realität angesiedelt, denn rational (aus menschlicher Sicht) ergäbe es kaum Sinn. Irreal auch, weil solch wacklige Gebäude könnten nie halten und darin leben könnte man auch nicht. Also rationalen Verstand weglegen und die Situation genießen.

Situation, denn viel passiert in den paar Minuten Spielzeit nicht. Es hat ein bißchen die Atmo eines Turmbaus zu Babel, eine verzweifelter, zum Scheitern verurteilter letzter Versuch (auch wenn er immerhin scheinbar über lange Zeit gut ging).

Etwas marode? 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : Keks

Gameplay

Laufen und Notizen lesen ist die Aufgabe. Vielleicht auch mal ein wenig am Turm weiterbauen.

Schwindelfreiheit erwünscht 
Une capture d'écran de Cloud Climber
Par : Keks

Technik

Das Spiel entstand wohl auf einer Game Jam. Dafür ist es beeindruckend. Ansonsten wäre es aber auch ein bißchen wenig.

Die Grafik ist recht interessant. Aus der Nähe wie gemalt, beinahe schwarz-weiß. In die ferne schweifend hat man einen weiten Blick auch auf entfernt liegende Türme, die aus den Wolken herausragen (warum dann noch höher gebaut wird?).

Der Sound ist sanft, unauffällig, aber angemessen.

Die Steuerung ist für Tastatur / Maus ausgelegt. Mit Controller funktioniert es auch.

Sonstiges

Nach 15 Minuten ist man wohl durch.

In Zahlen für mich persönlich ein Unterhaltungswert von 7/10.

Ein sehr kurzes, kostenloses Spiel (quasi eine Lauf-Sim) mit schöner Atmosphäre.


Dies ist mein subjektiver Spieleindruck. Für meine Wertung zählt, wie gut es mich unterhalten hat. Entsprechend der Daumen nach oben oder unten, abhängig davon, ob ich es einem ähnlich gesinnten Spieler weiterempfehle. Der Spieleindruck eines anderen Spielers kann aber durchaus stark davon abweichen.

Eine ähnliche Sicht auf das Spiel findet man beispielsweise hier.

9

1
20 minutes is the max you’ll ever spend in this game.
💲Price
10
It’s free!

🎮Storyline:
🔹 The title of the game is entirely accurate. Cloud Climber. When it ceased raining on Earth a thousand years ago, all of its water vanished into the clouds. People have been constructing towers to reach the clouds in an effort to collect water for the past 100 years. They have not been successful thus far. But have they finished building yet? Play to find out if they succeed in reaching the sky or spend the rest of their life constructing!

🎮Gameplay:
🔸 Identifying the game's exact motive is an extremely challenging job. Let's call it a walking simulator you can load up whenever you want to unwind for the next ten to fifteen minutes. The game doesn't actually have any true gameplay elements. Notes are used as a means to communicate the story to the player. The story is revealed as you read them, thus they are not hidden. It is quite difficult to ignore them because they are kept in plain view. The left click and the movement keys are the only keys you require. So, what precisely is the purpose of this game? The main goal of this walking simulator is to make you feel tranquil with its creative visual design and relaxing audio. Simply be present and take it all in!

📷Visuals and Audio:
🔹 When combined with the Borderlands-like visuals, the gloomy color palette creates an atmosphere that is difficult to forget. It's the ideal blending of visual and auditory components for a game with a post-apocalyptic setting. The entire game has a calming music, which is pretty much simply a basic melody yet is nevertheless calming. Is there something that makes you want to capture screenshots? Sincerely, no. But it may certainly help you if you want to take a break from the competitive grind!

For some reason, my laptop started heating very much just after 5 minutes of launching the game. Although it didn’t take a long time to finish it, please avoid playing the game if you do not have a good rig.

📝Main Pros and ♥♥♥♥:
Pros-
  • Free to play.
  • A relaxing experience.
  • Amazing art style.
  • Simple controls.

♥♥♥♥-
  • It’s very short.

😇Honest Rating:
🔸 Checking out this game is a no-brainer for the cost of free. Play this game if you desire serenity in your life for the next 15 minutes and are sick of competitive games.
(If you want to play a real game created by the same developer, I strongly suggest you check out Choo- Choo Charles! If you're interested, check out our review as well—unquestionably it's a 10/10.)

Rating: 8.5/10

Reviewer: Sha

Évaluation publiée le 29 janvier 2021
Produit reçu gratuitement

Cloud Climber is a very short walking simulator, with nice hand drawn graphics, and a brief story about why the builder build the towers. The time I played gave me a taster that made me want to see a full blown game expanded from this idea as the end came abruptly. (not that I was expecting anything less {or more}. Because the developer is giving this simulator away for free you really cannot go wrong downloading and checking it out. I found that it was worth the 15 to 20 minutes of time it should take to complete the simulation. You can actually complete it much faster if you ignore the messages, but that would defeat the point of this developers project. It actually took me almost 45 minutes to finish, but I was dragging my feet looking at the views and taking screen captures etc.

Basically you walk through a series of towers; moving ever-upwards, crossing bridges all made from wood and rope, and at one point even using an automatic pulley system {like they use between naval ships when transferring personnel quickly during conflict}. Early on in the game you need to find a key to be able to leave the first tower as the door to the bridge is locked. Also, there will be some repairs to a spiral staircase, plus near the end there is a bridge that you won't be able to cross until you've repaired the missing slats that allow you to cross. With those in mind, you'll need to find and pick up some planks of wood from a few stacks of timber on your journey upwards. The pulley system I mentioned above takes you to the penultimate tower, then you have to repair the bridge that takes you to the final brick and wood built tower.

The aim of the simulation is to gain the highest point of the group of towers. I wouldn't call it a game as it is far too short and there are virtually no game play elements, apart from a very brief interaction with several notes and planks of timber, plus finding a couple of keys. The interactive parts of the game glow white when you approach them. Just point your cursor over the object and click with the left mouse button to pick up, put down (fix), open or read whatever the interaction involves. Once you reach the top of the highest tower; the simulation ends.

Reading all of the notes and looking at the various viewpoints actually gave me a sense of melancholy for this lost civilisation. I love fantasy, survival and post apocalyptic stories and can become very involved with my games/stories/simulations, so was disappointed that it was so short; however, I would highly recommend you download and experience the simulation for yourself. It does have Very Positive reviews from the Steam community i.e. 92% from (1499 reviews). If you want to check out a full walk-through of the game you can see a 16 minute (minus 6 seconds) video (not mine) of game play HERE.

Stay safe in this time of doubt and lock-downs.
 
Whiterabbit-uk

[SHORT REVIEW]

What is "Cloud Climber"?

"Cloud Climber" is what you'd call a "walking simulator", played only with keyboard and mouse. It takes 15 minutes from start to finish. But it was one of the most melancholic, yet beautiful experiences I ever had in such a timespan.

The developer poured his heart into that game, which originally was created for a game jam, as he reveals in the (paid) Fan Pack DLC's developer commentary. And it shows. With just a few notes that you find throughout the game the story is conveyed in parts. You are left with a sense of wonder, but ultimately also a sense of beauty that is impossible to explain as it is not on a visual level but something that touches the soul.

I'd definitely recommend that you play through this once.

Cloud Climber is a beautiful hand-drawn walking simulator that encompasses art into philosophy. The game provokes thinking's on the future of humanism and the endless cycle of day and night.

The music played a huge roll in this since you are mostly walking above the clouds between towers. The mix of ethereal and casual tones transports you into the realm of this game.

This game takes about 15-20 minutes to complete, but it will feel like longer as you can simply stand on a ledge and look over the clouds and let the music take you away.

9/10 would recommend to anyone who is a fan of casual, artistic/poetry games. The only reason I am giving it 9/10 is because this game needs to be longer....it has such great potential and I look forward to playing more from this developer and their unique blend of poetry and almost hand drawn graphics.

Évaluation publiée le 24 novembre 2022
Produit reçu gratuitement

Cloud Climber ist ein kostenloses, superkurzes Walking Simulator Spiel, bei dem man nach rund 15 Minuten bereits am Ziel angekommen ist. Entsprechend darf man vom Spiel auch keine unglaublichen Storytiefen oder herausfordernden Rätsel erwarten. Aber lohnt sich so ein kurzes Intermezzo überhaupt?

Das kommt ganz darauf an, welche Präferenzen man hat. Wer Wert legt auf vollständige, eindeutige und abgeschlossene Geschichten, dem dürften bei Cloud Climber zu viele Fragen offen bleiben. Sowohl die Welt, in der das Spiel spielt, als auch deren Hintergrund bleiben ziemlich vage. Ebenso ist das Ende eher philosophisch, wobei es mich anders als bei anderen Spiele hier nicht gestört hat.

Dazu trägt zum einen, die Kürze des Spiels bei. Zum Anderen, hatte ich aber auch nicht das Gefühl, dass einem hier eine Philosophie oder Moral aufgedrückt wird oder das Spiel versucht, sich mehr philosophisches Gewicht zu geben, als es hat. Vielmehr ist es ein kurzes Eintauchen in eine fremde Welt, von der man ein Stück erlebt und die eher die Gedanken anregt, als dass es einen fragend oder frustriert zurücklässt.

Dazu hilft auch die toll gestaltete und stimmungsvolle Grafik und die gute Vertonung der Spielfigur. Alles zusammen gibt das ein äusserst stimmiges und unterhaltsames Gesamtpaket. Muss man Cloud Climber gespielt haben? Nein. Aber ich würde dennoch sagen, dass die 15 Minuten es absolut wert sind für ein kleines Eintauchen in eine interessante Welt.

Fazit: Ein spannendes, kostenloses Eintauchen in eine schön gestaltete und interessante Welt. Ein idealer kleiner Spielesnack für Zwischendurch.

"Cloud Climbers" is a short and sweet walking simulator that takes about half an hour to complete. It tells the story of a humanity struggling to build higher and higher into the sky to escape the unbearable droughts back on the Earth's surface - and from what I've seen, the art style and music/voiceover help immensely in delivering this narrative. You walk around the towers at your own leisure, making occasional repairs and rummaging through other people's belongings to uncover more of the beautiful and terrifying lore this game has to offer, and the more you dig, the more you find out of the other inhabitants' tragic fates. Overall, it's short, but not a waste of time to play through - and it's completely free on top of that!

Évaluation publiée le 14 janvier 2021
Cloud Climber is a very short, story-based free game by Gavin Eisenbeisz, of TwoStar games. The game's aesthetic takes much from his other two main projects, My Friend is a Raven, and My Beautiful Paper Smile, though Cloud Climber lacks the decayed grittiness of either of those games. It does however share with them a dystopian/apocalyptic feel, though in a far less urgent sense. The game takes place on a series of giant towers that humanity has been building for centuries, ever since the rain stopped generations ago. As the world's water supplies dwindled and eventually disappeared, the diminishing remnant of people built ever higher, questing for the clouds above in which, presumably, Earth's vanished water could be found. And now there's just you, the last person alive (as far as we know), trying to continue the work and also to decide if it's even worth doing anymore. Gameplay is very minimal, and not at all challenging; the story is clearly the point here, so Gavin obviously isn't trying to throw obstacles in between the player and seeing it unravel. From start to end it's about a fifteen minute sojourn, but interesting despite its brevity. Cloud Climber is short, engaging, and free, so what's not to like?

Évaluation publiée le 22 novembre 2023
Cloud Climber is a short, narrative-driven experience taking place in a post-apocalyptic world that is slowly dying due to a lack of water. You play as one of its last surviving inhabitants, a builder tasked with constructing towers to reach the clouds, in a desperate attempt to retrieve their water.

Something that's pretty apparent in the screenshots, but even more clear when you actually play the game, is that it's a very sombre experience. You get the impression from the get-go that there isn't really any hope left, and that the main character is basically just going through the motions at this point.

That's probably also why the gameplay in this one is pretty minimal. There's a couple of minor challenges, if you can really call them that, here and there, but overall it's carried by its story. Needless to say, it's only 10 minutes, so you might as well give it a try. I really enjoyed it.

If you would like to see a slightly more detailed version of this review, as well as reviews for other free to play indie games, be sure to check out my video for them here:

0.4 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 6 février 2021
Esse jogo é muito bom e conta a história de várias ''famílias'' que disputam por suprimentos para a sua própria sobrevivência porém sem qualquer empatia ou respeito pelos os outros. O jogo dá a entender que a construção das torres foi inicializada há mais de 100 anos por conta da escassez da água no planeta inteiro. Lendo cartas contemporâneas você entende o desespero dessas pessoas, já não chove a décadas e tudo está a ir por água a baixo, sem comida, sem água e sem material de construção as pessoas ficaram malucas e membros da própria família começaram a enlouquecer e se matarem. A guerra já não era entre as famílias mas sim entre tudo e todos. O nosso protagonista foi o único que ficou vivo pois teoricamente vivia sozinho na sua torre e já não tinha que dividir seus suprimentos com seus companheiros pois os mesmo já haviam morrido. A comunicação entre as torres é nenhuma até que os residentes morram e os sobreviventes próximos da torre abandonada a ocupem. Certo dia então o nosso protagonista acorda e tem a ideia de ir ver se os vizinhos estão vivos e caso não, ele iria continuar o seu trabalho a partir da torre que estivesse mais alta (mais próxima das nuvens), então ele embarca em uma viagem curta porém esclarecedora. Ao chegar no topo da torre cinco ele se cansa e desiste de continuar, dá para entender que ele trabalha na construção da torre dia e noite sem um único dia de folga, esgotado, ele senta na beira da torre mais alta e anuncia a sua pausa do trabalho, em seguida a chuva começa a cair porém a esgotamento do protagonista já era imenso, foi mais um alívio, um momento de felicidade genuína, uma recompensa depois de tantos anos pela busca da água. Eu imagino que ele tenha se matado logo depois. Incrível jogo.

Évaluation publiée le 9 avril 2021
My Experience

Cloud Climber represents such a tantalizing slice of a forlorn world. While the player is only privy to these few towers, I found myself imagining at length what life might look like beneath the clouds, if any existed at all.

The dusky palette and cel-shaded appearance of the towers is not only distinct, lending a strong sense of place, but it evokes the despair and despondency that many of us feel about impending climate change. We (but more importantly, multinational corporations) continue with business as usual, knowing that disaster is coming but lacking the collective foresight to take meaningful action.

Though short, this is a powerful game.

Évaluation publiée le 5 mars 2022
遊戲流程大概20分鐘，不看字會更短
這遊戲有一種末日荒涼的氣氛，手繪風挺美，劇情不錯，結局引人思考

故事大概說100年前開始發生水資源短缺的問題，而且有沙塵暴，那時人類的解決方法是建造一座座木塔
並由地面用升降機運送資源(水，食物，建材等等)來建高塔，目的是觸及雲朵來取得水資源供人生存，或者撐到旱災過去

而主角則是這些偉大工程的最後生存者，一天決定離開自己所在的木塔，查看其他人在木塔所留下的痕跡

Évaluation publiée le 29 janvier 2021
This might just be one of the shortest games I've ever played, lasing just over 15 minutes.
But even then, it makes you feel connected to the world that it presents to you.

The atmosphere is mysteriously pleasant even though it is just a few towers in a dust storm, the views are simple but beautiful and the notes left by the long gone builders depict real world human perspectives wonderfully. The narrator has also done a very good job at speaking in a very calming and relaxing tone, making each occasional narration a joy to hear.

I would definitely recommend the game to anybody looking for a short but sweet experience, and you don't even need to pay.

Enjoy! :)

Évaluation publiée le 10 mai 2021
Sigue a "La Cruceta Inquieta", mentor de Steam
"Cloud Climber" es un corto "walking simulator" en el que, durante unos escasos diez o quince minutos, podremos avanzar de torre en torre mientras disfrutamos de un estilo artístico bastante interesante y original, así como de un ligero argumento de trasfondo ecologista sobre la sobreexplotación de recursos naturales. Quien busque una experiencia compleja y alejada de lo que bien pudiera calificarse como una "demo", hará bien en alejarse del título; pero quien disfrute ♥♥♥ el mero hecho de recorrer mundos digitales que, más que contenido, dejen un poso para, ♥♥♥ posterioridad, hacer volar la imaginación, en "Cloud Climber" encontrará lo que busca.

Un "walking simulator" en toda regla, sólo apto para quien no espere algo más allá del disfrute de un corto recorrido a través de un pequeño pero bien construido mundo virtual.

Évaluation publiée le 24 juin 2021
É um jogo muito mais muito curto que pode ser concluído em 10-15 minutos (o que ultrapassei um pouco). Nele você tem que explorar cada torre para descobrir a história completa do que aconteceu e encontrar um caminho para a última torre para continuar o construtor mais alto. O jogo é uma experiência que descobre aos poucos a historia algumas pessoas que estavam nas torres que foram construídas a mais de 100 anos e seguindo o embalo disso há mil anos que parou de chover e toda a água da Terra evaporou nas nuvens. Então por mais de cem anos, as pessoas vêm construindo torres para tentar alcançar as nuvens, para que possam obter a água de que precisam para sobreviver e por mais de cem anos eles falharam. Agora é a vez do jogador conseguir e é isso que o jogo retrata.

0.4 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 22 février 2021
La tête dans les nuages.

Walk sim d'une durée de max 20 minutes, Cloud Climber est un jeu créé en game jam par Gavin Eisenbeisz, le développeur qui constitue à lui seul le studio Two Star Games.

En balade au sommet de tours inachevées qui avaient pour ambition d'atteindre les nuages, il nous suffit de suivre le chemin le plus évident tout récoltant au passage les objets placés sur notre trajet de façon très visible, comme des clés ou des outils, et en prenant le temps de lire les inévitables pages de journal qui fournissent la dimension narrative. Naturellement, il faut posséder au moins quelques bases en anglais pour tout comprendre.

La DA est cool, notamment les graphismes dessinés à la main. L'ambiance est visuellement bien moins sombre que dans les autres titres proposés par Eisenbeisz mais on reste résolument dans le thème post-apo qui semble bien l'inspirer.

Le jeu traite sans doute de l'absurdité du comportement humain, du manque de solidarité et du désastre écologique mais sans doute qu'on peut éventuellement chacun interpréter le message à sa façon à la toute fin.

Le même développeur propose deux autres titres gratuits sur Steam, en plus de son actuel gros projet encore en early access.


Courte escapade vers les nuages à prendre telle quelle, sans déplorer ce qu'aurait pu amener un contenu plus fourni.




Pour découvrir d'autres jeux du même développeur :
Lire mon évaluation de My Friend is a Raven
Lire mon évaluation de Night in Riverager

Non recommandé
0.3 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 20 mars 2023
I'd hate to give a negative review of a free game, but here it is.

First, my PC fans rev up like crazy. Task manager is reporting absurdly high CPU and GPU usage. It was like running a benchmark, even on low settings. Then, I see the problem, ~400 fps, but I can't find a setting to change it. Fortunately, I found this post, https://steamcommunity.com/app/1509820/discussions/0/4739443320530223720/. Why is an important setting off by default and hidden? I don't know.

Second, what you see in the trailer is the entire game. I'm not exaggerating. You walk around, ride that cart, place a few planks. That's it. There's no real story either.

Maybe I'm being a little harsh, but the truth is there's no real game here. If there was story or some eye candy, then it may be worth it. Unfortunately, it's no better than the trailer. I probably spent more time typing this review than completing the game.

TLDR: If you watched the trailer, then you've already seen everything.

Cloud Climber
A simple, yet beautiful post apocalyptic game where you climb different towers to understand why they are build, and the events that happened under the construction of them. The story in short is about humans that are building higher up into the skies, to reach the water they can't get on the surface. This is also why there are no humans left, simply because of the water shortage. Overall, it's a simple game, but a delightful and quite pretty one.

Évaluation publiée le 27 octobre 2022
Несмотря на симпатичный антураж, сомневаюсь, что стоит тратить на эту ходилку-бродилку даже 15 минут своего времени. Потому что все 15 минут мы идём в почти полной тишине (иногда слушая довольно заунывные речи главного героя) и читаем записки, проливающие хоть какой-то свет на произошедшее в игре *в смысле, предысторию*. Мы, разумеется, никаких интересных событий не увидим. Поэтому Cloud Climber можно смело назвать симулятором чтения записок в нарисованном вручную (по заверению создателей) 3D-пространстве.

Запоминающейся музыки здесь нет, сюжета как такового тоже, атмосфера за 15 минут не успевает погрузить в себя, потому как несмотря на красивый визуал, всё что мы видим - это нагромождение досок, лестниц и каких-то верёвок. В общем, самый большой вопрос - зачем это выпустили в свет и что я должен был из всего этого для себя вынести. Как по мне, получилось просто 15 минут приятно потраченного времени...

Если сравнивать, например, с мытьём пола или просто лежанием на диване в попытках придумать, чего ты хочешь на ужин. В общем, Cloud Climber - это просто ожившая картинка, внутри которой нам зачем-то дали возможность погулять.
 
Bauhaus_96

Évaluation publiée le 18 janvier 2021
Free very short exploration game.

If Franz Kafka had written a short story about a dry land where people build strange towers, and then turned it into a game, this is what it would look like. Be sure to open all of the doors and read all of the notes, or you'll miss out; 7 minutes is my "speedrun" time because I had played the game before.

Climb a tower today if you have 15 minutes or so!

Évaluation publiée le 18 janvier 2021
This is absolutely the best short game i have ever played.

It isnt like other walking simulator, its incredibly stunning, runs very well, and last but not least, has an incredible story of how rivers and oceans dry out (presumably). It follows the main character who is a male (because of his voice) in the future of humanity where all water has dried out on earth, and humanity in search of water, build towers to get water from the skies. It's a short 20 minute game at max, and its very relaxing and stress reducing. Happy ending aswell +1.

Évaluation publiée le 14 décembre 2022
This title as a whole is an interesting collection of ideas. When those ideas are separated they seem "meh I see your point but".

Gamplay

A literal walk from A to B.

100% walking sim: you won't be challenged or even have to think.

Interesting

The premise of the in-game world is an interesting one. The story concept and setting is very alien, unique and works well.

If you'd like a relaxing walk through the aftermath of an interesting story this is a good find.

"meh I see your point but"

I can easily understand that loads of people will not get it. I don't mean that as a negative towards anyone. I simply mean this title isn't for everyone.

A lot of people simply won't be able to take anything fun from this title and come to the conclusion: "meh I see your point but so what".

1 personne a trouvé cette évaluation utile

Recommandé
1.0 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 13 mars 2022
Świat przedstawiony w tej historii jest dziwny, ale ciekawy. Gra jest krótka, na około 20 minut, ale potrafi skutecznie zainteresować i po trochu odsłaniać jego tajemnice, chociaż na końcu można poczuć lekki niedosyt. Jest sporo notatek do znalezienia, można się dowiedzieć więcej o świecie i jego mieszkańcach, ale widać, że brakło trochę czasu, żeby nadać im odpowiedni wydźwięk.

Oprawa jest cudowna i świetnie tworzy melancholijny nastrój samotności pośród opuszczonych, monumentalnych dzieł ludzkich rąk. Na uwagę zasługują tekstury, wszystkie ręcznie rysowane, co nadaje grafice unikalnego, komiksowego stylu. Dźwięki są nienachalne i świetnie podkreślają klimat. Muzyka delikatna, nieustający odgłos wiatru jest kojący i niepokojący jednocześnie. Do tego myśli bohatera możemy usłyszeć i to bardzo miły akcent.

Polecam grę bardzo, a moja ocena to 8/10

It's ok. Short and free with a fun environment but a predictable story/ending. Has constant screen tearing even on a Gsync monitor; forcing fast vsync in nvidia control panel only made the game slow and mucky. There should've been broken chests on tower 3 to enforce story. The narrator is the dev and this was a game jam dump so of course it doesn't matter but the voice should've been more angry, tired, and emotional to the situations; instead it is poetic and soft which doesn't suit the workers nor what he is saying, went through, or is currently going through. This could;ve only been corrected by a professional VO artist and who in their right mind would get one for a game jam? lol So for what it is, bravo. Do wish the screen tearing wasn't a problem though :/

Évaluation publiée le 19 juin 2021
Une petite randonnée bien tranquille et à l'ambiance marquée !

Dans Cloud Climber, vous vivez en haut d'une immense tour inachevée, et votre personnage doit se réapprovisionner en eau. Un jeu extrêmement court, au point où c'en est un peu dommage (on aimerait en savoir plus sur cet univers dont on ne voit que les vestiges).

Le jeu vous tiendra en haleine, comme dit plus haut, par son ambiance bien marquée, un peu inspirée par Bendy and the Ink Machine (donc de la 3D, avec des textures très crayonnée, très dessinée, un style quasi monochromatique).

Si vous voulez vous lancer dans une petite aventure sans aucune pression, c'est fait pour vous. Par contre, sachez qu'on ne fait que marcher (donc pas de gameplay à proprement parlé) mais comme c'est pour une vingtaine de minute, une petite expérience ne fait jamais de mal.

Évaluation publiée le 11 juin 2021
You work hard, be it in school or your jobs. You enter your home, you sit down.

You load your favourite game, you play it for a while. There is one thing we all forget, however.

Gaming can be stressful. Toxicity exists within most games people choose to use to relax, in which you will be berated and insulted for trying your earnest or perhaps succumb to toxicity yourself.

I implore you, download this game. It may be anti-climactic and quite short but at least it is peaceful.
The graphics, despite being of a niche style, are beautiful. The audio is calming and the voice acting is soothing.

Take 15 minutes out of your day if you're getting a bit too worked up, install this and play it. Walk around slowly or just wander straight up over to the end. This game will bring you a sense of solace.

The Most Relaxing 15 Minutes On Steam, So Give It 15 Minutes Of Fame In Return.

122 produits enregistrés

1 personne a trouvé cette évaluation utile
0
Recommandé
0.3 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 25 mai 2021
Produit reçu gratuitement

This is a lovely little demo, and I look forward to seeing more work from this developer. The concept is neat, the graphics are well done, the brief story is tantalizing and well told, and the 20 minutes of game play here are quite fun.

I do have one important request for ALL future 3-D interface designs from this developer: you MUST include a "reverse Y-axis control" option. Seriously, something like half the population is mentally wired to see the view tilt downward when pushing the mouse or stick forward. That would include pilots like me who have a deeply ingrained expectation that pushing a stick forward will lower the nose. I was willing to tolerate the backward (to me) controls for this short, free game, but on a longer game or one I paid for this would be a deal breaker.

Other than that, excellent job.

Oh, and it runs great on Linux (Ubuntu 20.04 LTS) with the default Proton version in Steam.

kawazaki
0
1 personne a trouvé cette évaluation utile
0
Recommandé
0.5 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 24 janvier 2021
First off, if you are reading this and you have not yet downloaded and played this game, do it. You don't have to like a certain genre of game to enjoy this game. It is the best short-story based game I've ever come across. It doesn't give you insane amounts of lore and background, which I think makes to game 10 times better because you kind of have to imagine what really happened in your own mind. With the amount of lore the game gives us, I can give a description of what happened.
All of the world's water sources run dry. All the oceans, lakes, seas, everything. People start to think about building massive towers into the clouds to collect rainwater from the clouds. The character you control is a builder of one of the many towers that has spent his whole life building a single tower. Though the towers are connected in groups of 4, each tower is almost independent from the others. I won't say any more, because if you want to know more, play the game. It is worth it.
11/10

Évaluation publiée le 19 janvier 2021
Short and sweet walking simulator with an interesting story and surprise ending. The story follows a guy who is the last survivor in his community of towers, which his ancestors built to reach the clouds after earth's water dried up. As you make your way from tower to tower, you'll find notes that give clues about the story, as well as other people who used to live around you. I enjoyed the somber post-apocalyptic atmosphere, and the ending left me wondering what would happen next. It's free and can be completed in 10-20 minutes :)

Overall it was a great free 15 minute game and i would pay to have a similar or an extended version of the game.

This game is really beautiful. The story is basically a snippet and there's not much actual gameplay here beyond walking and "placing planks" in the most rudimentary way possible though. I think the beauty of the art design makes up for those weaknesses but your mileage may vary. It's a very short experience that is more "eye candy" than "game". As a sidenote: I'm compelled to provide a warning for anyone who, like me, is prone to experiencing motion sickness while gaming. There's a strange sort of lagging issue with the graphics rendering and I felt it's impact immediately. I still feel ill while writing this. The game is short so I powered through but if it had been even a minute longer I would have tapped out. Keep this in mind before deciding whether you want to play.

Évaluation publiée le 2 novembre 2022
Dying of thirst.

Story:

In the near future, water has dried up and people have resorted to building massive towers to reach the clouds to harvest water that way, however now even the clouds don't produce water. As the seemingly final human living in these towers you descend in the final hope of getting some water.

Cloud Climber has a very interesting story, although most of it is delivered behind pretty lengthy notes.. You basically encounter the remnants of the last humans and read through their thoughts about the hope of dying of thirst increasing over time. It's really cool stuff, but you have to love to read, cause there's quite a few notes to go through.

Graphics:

Very similar to the style of My Friend is a Raven. the world looks like a carboard cutout, but now everything is in first person. I love this art style and I think for this world the atmosphere is really good, walking around the towers and seeing no ground and just towers, as far as the eye can see and something about the atmosphere is really unsettling. It's a very similar visual flair, but the differences make this world feel it's own.

Audio:

The sound effects and soundtrack are great. I really enjoy how they help make the tone of the game somber, it really delivers on the whole factor of, world is dead and hope is bleeding out. It makes you feel like every step you make will likely be your last. There's also some voice acting, not a lot of it, but what's here is pretty decent, although nothing too impressive and I have to say the audio mixing feels a bit off.

Gameplay:

There's not much gameplay to speak of, Cloud Climber is basically a walking simulator and all you do is walk from point A to point B. Since it's pretty much like every other walking simulator, you have to like the genre, to appreciate this, since it's a pretty slow paced game and with the note reading, to people that get easily bored, it will be a slog to get through.

Verdict:

Cloud Climber is a great little short walking simulator. I really enjoyed the lore and the world set up and it was definitely worth the ten minutes it took to finish. It's a bit too slowly paced, but it's still worth checking it out if you're a fan of the genre.

Final Rating:
8/10

Pros:
+ Story is really intriguing
+ Visuals are great
+ The atmosphere is great

♥♥♥♥:
- A bit too slowly paced
- Some notes are a bit wordy

If you liked this review please consider joining https://steamcommunity.com/groups/completingthebacklog and https://steamcommunity.com/groups/ImperialReviews

あまりの短さにびっくりしました。実質１０分ぐらい。
部屋から出て階段を昇ったら終わりました。
雰囲気的には寂寥感があってよさげなのですが、とにかく何もやることがない。木造の高い塔の部屋でひゅるるる～と風に吹かれながらどんよりした雲を眺めてメモを読むだけです。
一人寂しく小屋からスタートして探検‥ならば　The Long Dark　で十分だし、残されたメモで謎解きしながら探索‥ならば　Home Sick 、内省的なのは　FIREWATCH があるのでこれは特にいらないかなぁといった感想。
まだ試作なのを少しだけ無料で流してみたのはわかります。
塔の見た目は全部一緒っぽいし、ストーリーはメモで進行、人物は１人称視点の自分のみ‥悲しすぎるほど低予算なんでしょうか。
木造の塔が重力と風雨に耐えられるのか、気になりすぎて話についていけません。このままなら完成してもたぶん買わないです。

Évaluation publiée le 30 juin 2021
As many others note, this isn't a game, but more of a very short walking sim. Very relaxing. Took me 23 minutes to wander through while listening to the narrator and reading the notes left behind by "game characters". The scenery is hauntingly beautiful, and the creator must have put a lot of effort into making those hand-drawn graphics.

However, the backstory, or history, is very shallow. The game description on the store page gives you more information of what's going on than what you learn in the game itself. Only the basics of the backstory are given to explain what led up to the point where you now find yourself. You must use your imagination to fill in the details of what happened.

The shortness of 'Cloud Climber' is most likely why it's free. A one-time play-through of a 20-minute story isn't really worth paying for, but it's awesome as a free item. Personally, I will go through it a second time just to enjoy another look at those graphics again.

Évaluation publiée le 24 février 2021
The concept and style are great. It has such a great back story that you discover while playing. I just wish the developer took it to the next step and expanded upon the story:
Keep the player finding new and increasingly complex ways to get to the next tower.
Discover more lore and explain what happened to the world.
Create a climactic point where they complete building a tower just in time so they can start collecting water from the clouds and keep humanity going.

I totally understand this was a solo project by one developer. So play this, knowing what one person created on their own. It's more than I could do!

It was a fun demo. It would be an extremely satisfying game.

Nice, short game (16 mins for me) about the last survivor of a tower-building community in a post-apocalyptic world.
Upon seeing the main menu, I was pleased to see this was from the same developer as My Friend is a Raven.
Spoilers? I wanted to see some sort of epilogue, or at least have some hope that the community could be rebuilt by the last survivor. Maybe there is some hope in the suppliers from ground level, but that'd a little extraordinary.
Bug: The "TowerGame.exe" and "TowerGame-Win64-Shipping.exe" processes do not close upon exiting of the game. I had to kill them.

Interesting little 10-15 minute experience, has a very Twilight Zone fable ambiance. Cuts right to the point with its message.

Visuals are pretty and hand-drawn. Ambient soundtrack is nice and fitting. It's a true walking sim, no challenge or gameplay besides "get to where you're going."

One thing I would have liked would have been voice acting on the notes for a little more flavor. I'm sure you could crowdsource some amateur VAs like me to read a couple lines of text for free-ninety-five. HMU lol

Really wish there was a third option for maybe, because this game was okay, in fact I would even say that the premise was interesting and the visuals were nice and artistic. Nevertheless, it ultimately felt over simplistic and too short. Whilst there is a good reason for this (it was made to be a short game for some game awards I believe), to me it felt too short to justify spending my time on, so it just felt like an 11 minute waste of time with some mediocre gameplay and a vaguely interesting premise that wasn't sufficiently explored through the course of those 11 minutes. Whilst it is free, and so cannot be a waste of money, I don't recommend the game as I found it to be a waste of time.

Évaluation publiée le 8 octobre 2021
DISCLAIMER: This is a full review, and NOT a first impressions review

Cloud Climber is a game developed by Two Star Games and published by V Publishing

The game offers some nice graphics and a really beautiful aesthetic, although some ugly glitches here and there, it is pleasant all the same

The game does suffer with some repetitiveness at certain areas of the game but a fun game nonetheless

Cloud Climber overall, however, is a fun game to play, yet sometimes repetitive and it does get boring if being played for a long time, but is a really good short casual game to play in short bursts!

RECOMMENDED :)

Évaluation publiée le 24 mars 2021
A great game that leaves a lot to the imagination. (in a good way! I'm not saying this like it's missing anything or needs anything more, it's almost like a book where your mind wanders and imagines the world and what happens in it. )

The thoughtsI had while playing this narrative adventure:

-Why did people start building this high? What happened on the ground? What does it look like?
-Are people trying to climb back up the towers?
-What happens when too many people try to climb up a tower? Do they have to block them somehow?
-If everyone is gone, what happened to them?
-Have any towers toppled over? What would that look like? Feel like? Sound like?
-Resources are scarce, how do people hunt, eat, get water? Hunt birds? Trap birds/animals?
-Do people extract water from the clouds / catch and store rain. How and what inventive ways have they found to survive up here.
-How do people deal with weight issues. Too many people would be bad for a tower.
-Wind issues, what is done to help from wind.

And all kinds of cool things, I love the concept, great little game, art style is cool as well.

Cheers,

Produit reçu gratuitement

It is not a game, it is an interactive story. It's not bad, but I wouldn't recommend it for a game site. The story is interesting enough. The developer needs to realize you shouldn't have 100 saws and only one of them is pickup-able. 100 chests - only 2 of them open. That's terrible gaming.

Also, moving in circles to read 10-20 letters that tell a story is not compelling. The few things that you could do quickly became arduous.

If you're looking for a game, not recommended. If you're looking for 20 minutes to be told a 3-minute story, this is your game.

Évaluation publiée le 14 janvier 2021
The story for Cloud Climber is of a lone character as he goes about his 'work' to reach and continue to build the last tower. For simple reference the origin of the towers reminded me of Noahs Ark. Along the way you read some stories of the World and inhabitants as you ponder your purpose. Its a story every human can relate.

I really love the look of the game and it ran flawless. However it did crash on my first play through at the very end. The game is only 15-20 minutes if reading everything so it was easy to run though again and see the ending.
Hopefully this is maybe just a test/ concept for a future exploration/ puzzle adventure because its a World you would want to see more.

Personne n'a trouvé cette évaluation utile
0
Recommandé
0.6 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 15 aout 2021
This is a fairly unique game in its art style. I've never played anything like it. Yet it was oddly satisfying as it was very slow paced (no pun intended!). As walking sims gain ground (again, no pun intended) in popularity, games like this show me that I don't need all my games to be fast-paced action all the time. Gems like this give me food for thought imagining a future where water has become so scarce that mankind starts building towers to the clouds to claim their moisture. I wouldn't call this a "game" per se, more a very short visual study on why mankind might be so obsessed with running the race of life that often what's going on around us gets lost in the details.

Évaluation publiée le 9 octobre 2021
This should have been a short story and it could have been good. As it is, this is not a game. As my first foray into the walking simulators (I've been sucessfully keepeing away from them until now), it is extremely short, with hardly anything that can be called gameplay. Which is a shame, as more thinking about how to make this a game the player can be engaged with would have done wonders for it. So here is why I've reluctantly given a negative review:

Pros:

+ graphics style
+ atmosphere
+ base idea

♥♥♥♥:

- extremely short! (not kidding, just look at the time played, that is the whole game)
- feels like an idea that should have ended as a game, but then no actual gameplay happens
- no thinking and hardly any action done by the player
- the character monologue is lacluster (doesn't show personality and thus isn't engaging)
- greatly missed opportunity of visual storytelling (many notes could have been made into actual visual content)
- no intrigue (yes, you are supposed to wonder why you are building and climbing thsese towers, but as it all gets spelled out for you in the above mentioned lackluster monologue, it just doesn't keep you wondering)

All in all, a short story or a short movie would have been in both cases a better alternative. Or a LOT of thought and work put into making this game have actual gameplay involved. The potential IS there, it just gets completely unused. Shame, really.

Évaluation publiée le 20 juillet 2021
I is weird for me to find myself not recommending a free game. And yet, here we are.
It's a walking sim alright, in the worst sense of the word. You just walk around a literally and metaphorically blank map as a stereotypical postapocalyptic tale with the classic "sad" background drones on without any of the self awareness of the better half of such stories. All to hammer home a philosophical message that is as blunt as it is simplistic.

There are no puzzles, no branches on the path, no mystery, nothing to stimulate the brain and nothing to really do. Even worse it also gets self indulgent towards the end. The Return of the Obra Dinn this most definitely isn't. I wasted my time playing this, and I feel it was in fact just not worth it, even for free. So I will tell you to avoid it.

Maybe if you're into walking sims to an extreme degree. If you wake up every night with a cold sweat thinking "oh god I need my fix of walking around an empty husk of a map while a narrator tells me how sad everything is", if you just can't get enough letters detailing the tragedy called life through the lenses of characters that are doomed to die in boring and predictable fashion. Maybe then... after you've finished all the others. If you literally have nothing better to do. Then I'd tell you to go take a walk in the park while you listen to Edgar Alan Poe.

Like others, wish I could give this a "thumbs neutral" instead of thumbs down.

* Free
* Nice graphics
* Peaceful (no running from monsters or QTE's or other stressful junk)

♥♥♥♥:

* No controls setup (so left-handed trackball + right-handed keypadders like me are SOL)
* No mouse invert look
* Linear; little exploration
* Little story, little explanation, and story that is told is trying too hard to seem "deep"

You're just there, you walk a bit, you read journals, you listen to yourself narrate stuff, then it's over.

You get what you pay for.

Produit reçu gratuitement

The game looks good but there's barely anything in it. I walked into the game with enthusiasm after watching the game's intriguing trailer. I walked out of this game feeling like my the developer stole 16 minutes of my time. The story (If you could even call it a story) is about a construction worker who's stuck in a tall cloud-reaching wooden tower that he and his co-workers built for quite some time. A construction worker's function is to look up into the sky and try to reach it by tall building towers. But the tragedy of the story is that the workers never looks down. They keep looking at the stars to prolong their life but they forgot to look down upon the towers and appreciate what they have; what they created. They forgot to appreciate 'The moment'. Perhaps my main complaint is that the game has an interesting storyline can be read through the multiple letter we stumble into, but it all amounted to nothing. And we weren't given a reason why the main character didn't leave the towers while the others did. The amounting boredom in gameplay and underwhelming ending can't make but make the game feel unfinished.

Évaluation publiée le 15 janvier 2021
The game is fine, it's got an interesting setting. It's short, but for something free it was worth the time. For what it is the voice acting is serviceable. The textures are nice. There was some pretty bad screen tearing at the last tower though.

The reason I'm not really recommending it, is that the game wouldn't close properly. I had to close Steam and force the game to exit that way, and after uninstalling it didn't do it properly. It was still on my computer despite Steam not registering it as installed (it would prevent a fresh download/install though). And I had to restart my computer in order to actually get rid of it because it was still in use.

Obviously results may vary on this issue, my computer is pretty old at this point, but I can't get over having these issues and being able to recommend it outright. I spent more time trying to figure out what happened with the game's issue here than actually playing it and making sure I actually had it uninstalled. While I liked the game, it wasn't worth the hassle it ended up being for me. (and at least a few had the issue with not closing)

The developers have fixed the issue. I redownloaded it just to see if it worked properly on my end and it closes properly and uninstalled properly. So the only reason I had for not recommending it is no more so give it a whirl. Thanks to the devs for fixing the issue.

Évaluation publiée le 18 janvier 2021
Cloud Climber is an extremely simplistic walking sim about people building their own stairway to heaven, but ultimately meeting their real fate due to poor food / water rationing and dire consequences following. Life on the ground floor has become insufferable and fruitless, with every source of water quickly drying up. What other option than to grab a bunch of clouds and squeeze out every drop yourself? And thus, the possibly tallest towers to ever crafted by man emerged, surpassing various layers of water-filled pillows.

According to the first document we stumble upon, our protagonist Stan appears to be the only survivor left, standing on the planks of a 100-years-old structure. He decides to head out and inspect the remains of his neighbours across the bridge, though he finds nothing but more notes. Reminiscing about the past, as he makes his way across to the third and fourth towers, he reaches the top and sits down to admire their reaction, saying he hasn't had time to do so ever since they started building (I honestly thought he was going to jump at that moment). And that's conveniently when the layers above darken up and the rain starts falling. A possible continuation?

It takes less than 10 minutes to walk through and it isn't exactly the greatest achievement on a technical level, you've only got presets and mouse sensitivity in the settings, v-sync has to be enabled manually from the graphics panel. Performance hasn't been at all problematic to me, everything ran consistently well. Not super-excited about further development on this project, but I'll be there if they continue working on it.
 
Яedly Яed.暗赤色@Tsundere-Tiddy

Cloud Climber was okay at best. As a short tragedy in the form of a game, it felt underwhelming. The game only lasts ~15 minutes if you read everything, 12 if you don't.
Unfortunately, this game falls into the trap of having more invisible barriers than a modern triple A game and has a small amount of backtracking. The story can be summarized as "protagonist is the last person alive after a 100-year long drought. You read some diary entries and then it rains."
It is definitely has more of the feel of a test or a proof of concept for first person games by Two Star. This game is not bad, but i would not recommend playing it.

Évaluation publiée le 22 janvier 2021
Not recommended, mainly because it cooks your PC.

First off, I love dystopian worlds. The world setting is quite appealing with its beautiful graphics and some interesting story bits about life in primitive towers that reach into the clouds. Sadly, the concept is flawed, game play is lacking (walking sim) and its very short. I would have given it a thumbs up though since its free, but this game is unoptimized. My PC fans kicked in for the first time in a very long time when I was on the 4th tower. It had me concerned to be honest since they never turn on. I can only imagine the potential damage this can do to a budget PC and for that reason alone, I advise to pass on this one.

3,904 produits enregistrés

Personne n'a trouvé cette évaluation utile
0
Non recommandé
1.5 h en tout
Évaluation publiée le 21 janvier 2021
Initially created for the 2020 Epic MegaJam with the theme ‘it’s been a long time, but we’re not done yet‘, Cloud Climber is a short narrative driven walking-simulator about what might happen in a world without water. Set a thousand years after the rain stops and after over a hundred years of construction, the player is one of the last remaining people alive with all hope resting on building higher into the clouds.

Cloud Climber presents players with a mixed bag with its appealing visuals, contemplative play style and unfortunate narrative disarray. It is an interesting concept with undeniably original aspects but the lack of perceivable logic behind the basic premise of the game is jarring and hard to overcome. It’s also worth noting the poor optimisation that resulted unjustifiably high CPU usage! All that being said, it was an impressive feat for one person to create the entire game within a week and it was a pleasant way to spend ten to fifteen minutes, especially for free!

WANT MORE INFO ON WHY I DON'T RECOMMEND THIS GAME?
My full review on Cloud Climber, where I do into detail about styling, narrative, gameplay and performance can be found at Indie Hive[indie-hive.com].

Évaluation publiée le 17 janvier 2021
I didn't really dislike this "game" — more an exercise than an actual game — but I don't feel like "Very Positive" is fair, so I'm adding a negative vote to aim for balance.

The story here is odd at best, and woefully fragmented at worst. I just don't buy the central premise, and the few notes we find along the way don't shed much light on the Why. Gameplay is minimal.

The atmosphere is excellent, with hints of MYST. But whereas that game has an actual mystery to solve and characters hiding in the edges, this project has a few (mostly disconnected) notes and lots of talking. (I wasn't crazy about the voice acting, but it's okay I suppose.)

The creator of this project obviously has talent, and I would play a longer game from the same studio. But this one underwhelmed me.

Évaluation publiée le 16 janvier 2021
TL;DR at the end*

A very short-lasted and easy gameplay which makes sense 'cause the game is not more than 300mb. But it wasn't boring at all; the concept was engrossing more or less and the diegesis could have been improved, considering the fact that there were only a bunch of letters left to read by some random people for whom nobody cares about.

Overall:
Nicely-built World
Somewhat Mysterious Plot
Nice Narrating
Great Concept
Very Easy Gameplay
Buggy but easily unnoticeable movements/physics

Lastly, if this exact concept were to be adopted into a full-fledged puzzle-type game with a long-lasting gameplay and put more effort into it, this could've easily been a banger; and only due to the fact that this ain't a fully-fledged puzzle-type mystery game, I can't recommend this to anyone, unless the creator decides to upgrade this 7 day project into something better. Still, if you have 300mb space and 15 mins to spare, try it for yourself, who knows....you might like it or, in a worst case scenario, hate it.


TL;DR: Just do what you want, either leave it or play it, who cares?!

Évaluation publiée le 17 janvier 2021
He tardado más en hacer esta reseña que lo que dura el juego...

ANÁLISIS DE Cloud Climber:

Otro juego gratuito de la mano de los creadores de My friend is a Raven (análisis AQUÍ). En esta ocasión el apartado visual, aunque similar, no sorprende tanto como en su anterior juego. Eso sí, en la configuración "Epic" está mejor optimizado.

Está completamente en inglés, tanto voces como textos, así que no lo recomiendo a quienes no entiendan el idioma ya que hay bastante texto teniendo en cuenta la duración.

Hace miles de años que ha dejado de llover y el agua de la tierra se ha evaporado en las nubes. La gente ha estado construyendo torres para intentar alcanzar las nubes y poder tomar el agua que necesitan para vivir. La idea parece que no llegó a funcionar, argumento que explica mediante la narración del protagonista y por medio de varias notas de texto que encontraremos en las torres.

PROS:

- Es gratis

- Mejor optimizado que My Friend is a Raven en la máxima configuración

- El apartado visual, muy original

- Tiene mensaje

CONTRAS:

- Muy corto, dura menos de 15 minutos

- Completamente en inglés

- No tiene logros

- Los objetos se repiten en exceso

- Se hace aburrido

- No llega al nivel de My Friend is a Raven

Conclusión:
No me ha parecido suficiente como para valorarlo positivamente. Solo recomendaría darle una oportunidad si entiendes bien el inglés y quieres jugar una experiencia corta (menos de 15 minutos) relajada y ♥♥♥ algo de mensaje. Eso siempre que no tengas nada mejor que jugar, y seguro que tienes muchas opciones mejores ♥♥♥ las que ocupar tu tiempo.

Si mi análisis te ha gustado o te ha servido de ayuda, agradecería que dejaras un voto positivo para que pueda llegar a más gente. También se agradecen los premios. ¡Gracias por leerme! No dudéis en dejar vuestros comentarios o dudas, responderé lo antes posible.

>>>¿Quieres jugar gastando poco dinero? ¡haz clic aquí para seguir mi página de mentor si quieres ver mis análisis de juegos gratuitos, baratos o en oferta!<<<

Évaluation publiée le 15 janvier 2021
The beginning of the description is VERY accurate. This title is very short that I was able to complete in 16 minutes. And I agree with other reviews that the game is very nice looking. The style is great, it reminds me a lot of Bendy.

However, to call this title thought provoking and to suggest it tells a unique and compelling story is a bit of a stretch. I was left wanting to know more about the the story that led up this game. Is everyone dead on the other towers too? Did that guy push the other off on purpose?

Here is how I see this game fulfilling that "Casual" game feel. Develop the towers in a way that they continuously change by level. A vertical labyrinth. Just allow it to go on forever.

How the game stands now, I really don't recommend spending the short amount of time to download, install and uninstall this game. It's just not worth it.

Really, really short - I wish there was more to it, but what little of the vibes and atmosphere I got was interesting. I liked the premise of a dystopian universe where people keep building to reach the clouds for water and never really get there; the landscape was really something and the voice acting wasn't half bad. It was just too short for there to be any real story except for the few snippets I got from the leftover journal entries, and it was never explained how the main character was the only one left standing. I'd recommend this for a brief exploration of a concept, but I wouldn't consider it much of a game; if it were expanded upon, though, it could be pretty good.

Évaluation publiée le 1 novembre 2022
Cloud Climber is a short demo, a basic walking sim with lightweight first person adventure elements. You climb up a series of towers in a linear fashion, stopping to read flavour text that will dutifully inform you that apparently all the water dried up on the earth so people built towers so they can harvest water from the clouds. Righto.

The game is very, very simple, and very, very short. It feels like a demo/showcase, and not a serious attempt to make a PC game for gamers.

From a technical perspective, the game doesn't meet basic minimum requirements that most PC gamers expect as standard.

There's no options to change the resolution for the game or customise the graphics settings. There's no way for gamers to ensure this is running at the native resolution of their displays... there's no guarantee this game will look right on any PC as a result of this hamfisted design decision. There's no way for gamers to try improve the low quality graphics.

The game features lazy low-polygon "retro" assets, and while they have an almost tasteful "hand drawn art" texture set all over them, this isn't used well in the context of the game, and has been done much better by others.

The controls can't be customised, which will be an annoyance for many, but it can also render the game unplayable for differently-abled gamers.

These technical defects push this game below acceptable standards for any modern PC game.

The game isn't really free as the developers have their hands out for paid donation DLC, basically digital panhandling, but you can complete the whole thing without paying any money if you want.
